career macroeconomic implications of gender roles and consumer credit markets using quantitative life cycle models for policy analysis siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr centers programs projects education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home research at siepr research project career macroeconomic implications of gender roles and consumer credit markets using quantitative life cycle models for policy analysis title career macroeconomic implications of gender roles and consumer credit markets using quantitative life cycle models for policy analysis principal investigator michele tertilt dates march 1 2008 february 28 2013 sponsor national science foundation the proposed career development plan consists of research and educational projects centered around building and using general equilibrium models of life cycle behavior to analyze various institutions and policies the research comprises two different components 1 research on the macroeconomic causes and consequences of gender roles and 2 the analysis of consumer credit markets both components share a common methodology by using computed dynamic macro style models to study the interaction between policies and household behavior the research will make both theoretical contributions and address concrete applied questions stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
